<exercise number="1"><statement><p>At what time do the hands of a clock form a 90<m>\degree</m> angle? At what time do they form a straight angle?</p></statement>
<answer><p>3 o'clock, 6 o'clock</p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="2"><statement><p>A rectangle has four right angles. What is the sum of the angles in a rectangle?</p></statement></exercise>

<exercise number="3"><statement><p>Is it possible for a triangle to have more than one obtuse angle? Why or why not?</p></statement>
<answer><p>No. The sum of the angles would be more than 180°.</p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="4"><statement><p>What can you say about the sum of the two acute angles in a right triangle?</p></statement></exercise>

<exercise number="5"><statement><p>The word "vertex" has several meanings in mathematics. Describe two ways it is used in this lesson.</p></statement>
<answer><p>The point where the two sides of an angle meet, and the angle between the equal sides of an isosocelels triangle.
</p></answer></exercise>

<exercise number="6"><statement><p>Can two acute angles add up to a straight angle? Why or why not?</p></statement></exercise>

